1. Variables + Strings
let str = "Rohan Tosh";

str.length;
str.toUpperCase();
str.toLowerCase();
str.substring(1, 5);
Used for basic string operations like length, case change, and slicing.

2. Math Operations
a + b
a - b
a * b
a / b
a % b
Basic arithmetic operations.

3. Comparison (Logical)
a > b
a < b
a == b
a != b
a >= b
a <= b
Used to compare values → result is true or false.

4. Object
let obj = {
  name: "Alice",
  age: 30,
  city: "New York"
};

obj.name;
obj.age;
Stores data in key-value pairs.

5. Dynamic Typing
let str2 = "Aryan";
str2 = 23;
JS allows changing type at runtime (string → number).

6. Function
function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
}
Simple reusable code block.

7. Const vs Let vs Var
const c = 5;

let l = 5;
var v = 6;
Difference:
const → cannot change
let → block scoped
var → function scoped (older, risky)

8. Block Scope Example
{
    let l = 10;
    var v = 20;
}
let stays inside block, var escapes block.

9. Conditions
if (i > j) {
    console.log("i is greater");
} else {
    console.log("j is greater");
}
Basic decision making.

10. Switch Case
switch(choice) {
    case "A":
        console.log("Choice A");
        break;
    default:
        console.log("Invalid");
}
Used for multiple conditions.

11. Array + Loop + Type Check
for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if(typeof arr[i] === "number") {
        console.log(arr[i], "is number");
    }
}
Loop through array and check data type.

12. typeof Operator
typeof str
typeof obj
typeof arr
Used to check data type of variables.